                            <comment id="14295837" author="blerer" created="Wed, 28 Jan 2015 20:49:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Those 3 patches fix the problems for the 3 versions that support multi column restrictions.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14295840" author="blerer" created="Wed, 28 Jan 2015 20:51:37 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;While working on this problem I discovered that there was 2 issues with multicolumn restrictions and secondary indices:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The first problem was caused by the fact that the code was not retrieving the proper value for the clustering column &lt;tt&gt;IndexExpression&lt;/tt&gt; when multicolumn restrictions were being used. This problem could be reproduced by the unit test provided in the description&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The second problem was that for the table:
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;CREATE TABLE test (a &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, b &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, c &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, d &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, e &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, f &lt;span class=&quot;code-object&quot;&gt;int&lt;/span&gt;, PRIMARY KEY ((a, b), c, d, e))&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;the following query:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&quot;code panel&quot; style=&quot;border-width: 1px;&quot;&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;codeContent panelContent&quot;&gt;
&lt;pre class=&quot;code-java&quot;&gt;SELECT * FROM test WHERE a = ? AND (c) IN ((?), (?)) AND f = ? ALLOW FILTERING&lt;/pre&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;was working fine if the clustering column &lt;tt&gt;c&lt;/tt&gt; was not indexed but was rejected if it was.&lt;br/&gt;
The reason was that the code was trying to create an &lt;tt&gt;IndexExpression&lt;/tt&gt; for the &lt;tt&gt;c&lt;/tt&gt; column which was not needed.&lt;br/&gt;
This problem was also affecting single column restrictions.  &lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14303698" author="thobbs" created="Tue, 3 Feb 2015 18:17:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Review comments:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;tt&gt;SelectStatement.restrictedNames&lt;/tt&gt; could use a comment explaining what the values in the map mean&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The two unit tests that are expected to fail are missing the table name in the 2.0 patch&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the trunk patch, &lt;tt&gt;SingleColumnPrimaryKeyRestrictions.addIndexExpressionTo()&lt;/tt&gt; could use comments explaining the logic.  It&apos;s not clear why we only check &lt;tt&gt;isClusteringColumn()&lt;/tt&gt; once, what &lt;tt&gt;position&lt;/tt&gt; is tracking, and why &lt;tt&gt;CONTAINS&lt;/tt&gt; is treated specially.  Also, typo in the  &lt;tt&gt;clusteringColumns&lt;/tt&gt; variable name.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In 2.0, this appears to cause a regression in the dtest &lt;tt&gt;CQLTests.simple_tuple_query_test()&lt;/tt&gt;.  It throws an IRE when the query should be supported.  I&apos;m not sure if we need &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-8613&quot; title=&quot;Regression in mixed single and multi-column relation support&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-8613&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-8613&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; applied at the same time to fix this.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Also in 2.0, in the dtest &lt;tt&gt;CQLTests.composite_index_with_pk_test()&lt;/tt&gt;, we&apos;re not requiring &lt;tt&gt;ALLOW FILTERING&lt;/tt&gt; (where I believe we should be), causing a test to fail.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;I didn&apos;t run the dtests against 2.1 or trunk, but I recommend running at least &lt;tt&gt;cql_tests.py&lt;/tt&gt; against the patches for those branches.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14305152" author="blerer" created="Wed, 4 Feb 2015 14:28:43 +0000"  >&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;In 2.0, this appears to cause a regression in the dtest CQLTests.simple_tuple_query_test(). It throws an IRE when the query should be supported. I&apos;m not sure if we need &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-8613&quot; title=&quot;Regression in mixed single and multi-column relation support&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-8613&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-8613&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; applied at the same time to fix this.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I had a look at the test and the failing query is effectively caused by  &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/CASSANDRA-8613&quot; title=&quot;Regression in mixed single and multi-column relation support&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;CASSANDRA-8613&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;CASSANDRA-8613&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;. I am working on it and it should be ready in a couple of days.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;p&gt;Also in 2.0, in the dtest CQLTests.composite_index_with_pk_test(), we&apos;re not requiring ALLOW FILTERING (where I believe we should be), causing a test to fail.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The patch was effectively introducing a regression.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14306858" author="blerer" created="Thu, 5 Feb 2015 08:46:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The previous patch for 2.0 was the only one affected by the regression problem. I added some explanation in all the other patches.&lt;br/&gt;
I have run the DTests and I did not see any other errors related to the patches.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14314940" author="thobbs" created="Tue, 10 Feb 2015 21:11:53 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1, committed as &lt;tt&gt;9649594c761dbb72&lt;/tt&gt;.  Thanks!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
